    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="244"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d244">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.20/803</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1866</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-20">March 20,
                            1935</date>.<lb/>[Received March 29.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I wish to express my thanks to the Department for
                    its Circular Telegram of March 18, 7 p.m.,<note n="48" xml:id="d244fn48">See
                        footnote 42, <ref target="#pg_301">p. 301</ref>.</note> received via the
                    Paris Embassy, giving consensus of the American press reaction to Hitler’s
                    announcement that the Reich would increase its national defense forces.</p>
                <p>This review of the American press is especially helpful to us here in view of the
                    efforts of the German press to make it appear that America, at the most, was
                    indifferent to the Chancellor’s action and inclined to accept it as inevitable
                    and justifiable in view of increased armaments of other nations.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William E. Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
